:content
Let $m_m and $m_n be two positive integers. A $m_m&times'$m_n <em>matrix</em>
is a table of $m_m$m_n elements arrayed in $m_m lignes and $m_n colonnes. 
The matrix is <em>real</em> if the elements are real numbers, or
<em>complex</em> if they are complex numbers, etc.
<p>
For example, 
!insmath [1,pi;e,-3]
 is a real 2&times;2 matrix, and

!insmath [1,i,3;4,5,pi-i;-i,-1,-1]
 is a complex 3&times;3 matrix.
<p>
One may write a general $m_m&times;$m_n matrix by
<p><center>

!read primitives.phtml 1, embed, matmn, A&nbsp;=&nbsp; 

</center><p>
or abridged to ($m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>). The $m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>
are called <em>coefficients</em> of A, and $m_m&times;$m_n is its <em>dimension</em>.
<p>
Two matrices A and B are equal only if they are of the same dimension,
and have the same coefficient at every corresponding position.
<p>

